Amplicon Sequencing analysis

Report by Carlos Neves

for the Sophia Genetics position for Bioinformatician.

Task description:

This report analyses the Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) reads for human DNA regions using a pair-ended amplicon sequencing design on a Miseq sequencing platform. The data was provided by Sophia Genetics as the compressed file sequenceFile.zip, which contains the raw fastq reads file and the alignment (hg19 human genome) file in BAM format.

The primers used for the target sequencing were:

sequences <- list(
    "primer_forward_1" = "TTGCCAGTTAACGTCTTCCTTCTCTCTCTG",
    "primer_reverse_1" = "GAGAAAAGGTGGGCCTGAGGTTCAGAGCCA",
    "primer_forward_2" = "CCCTTGTCTCTGTGTTCTTGTCCCCCCCA",
    "primer_reverse_2" = "CCCCACCAGACCATGAGAGGCCCTGCGGCC",
    "primer_forward_3" = "TGATCTGTCCCTCACAGCAGGGTCTTCTCT",
    "primer_reverse_3" = "TGACCTAAAGCCACCTCCTTA",
    "primer_forward_4" = "CACACTGACGTGCCTCTCCCTCCCTCCA",
    "primer_reverse_4" = "CCGTATCTCCCTTCCCTGATTA",
    "adapter_1" = "AAGACTCGGCAGCATCTCCA",
    "adapter_2" = "GCGATCGTCACTGTTCTCCA")

Please note that this report focuses on solving the following questions using the R language. Alternative methods are available and it is not uncommon to used various languages/software to solve these problems.

Questions:

  1. What is the constitution of each read, for example (adaptor + primer + amplified region)?

Answer: Each read will be constituted by forward primer + amplicon + reverse primer. However, because the read length is not long enough to span the entire amplicon, these reads will not correspond to the full amplicon sequence. The adapters are not present in the read as these are already hybridized (double-stranded) and thus are not “synthesized” during sequencing.

Confirmation: Using the ShortRead library the presence/absence of the primers and adapters were confirmed in the raw reads from the FASTQ files aln1.fastq.gz and aln2.fastq.gz.

Few adapters are found in the FASTQ files, while the primers commonly match perfectly to the read start. For aln1.fastq there are 489 411 reads with one of the primers (450 638 at the read start) out of 575 002 reads, suggesting 78-85% of the reads may correspond to the expected sequences. For aln2.fastq there are 504 463 reads with one of the primers (409 605 at the read start) out of 575 002 reads, suggesting 71-88% of the reads may correspond to the expected sequences.

Using the predicted sequence for each amplicon, the editing distance between these and the experimental reads was estimated (taking into account the read size of 151 bp). The total number of reads with a edit distance less than 5 were used to assess how many reads correspond to the expected sequences.

# Convert the amplicon sequence vectors to a DNAStringSet object
amplicons <- DNAStringSet(amplicons)

# Estimate the forward distances to each amplicon 
for_dist <- srdistance(sread(aln_1), substr(amplicons, 1, 151))

# Estimate the reverse distances to the reverse comliment of each amplicon
rev_dist <- srdistance(sread(aln_2), 
                   substr(reverseComplement(amplicons), 1,151))

# Generate all possible distances (names) smaller than 5
dists <- as.character(seq(0,5,0.25))

null_return <- sapply(1:length(for_dist), function(idx) {
    cat(paste("Primer pair", idx, 
    "\nNumber of sequences with distance < 5 on aln1:\n", 
    sum(table(for_dist[[idx]])[dists], na.rm=TRUE),
    "\nNumber of sequences with distance < 5 on aln2:\n",
    sum(table(rev_dist[[idx]])[dists], na.rm=TRUE), "\n\n"))
})

2. Which gene region did those reads mapped to ?

Answer: Most of the reads aligned to chromosome 7 (86%), as it would be expected, since the primers are targeting EGFR exons, a gene found in this chromosome. Of all the reads mapping to chromosome 7, 50% show some mapping overlap with the four amplicons considered.

1 052 966 reads aligned to either the human sex chromosomes or the autosomes, which corresponds to 91% of all reads. In respect to the unmapped reads, these are most likely an artefact of the seqeuncing method, as low diversity libraries (such as for amplicon sequencing) usually require a DNA spike-in. A common choice for external DNA is the phiX phase DNA. To confirm this, the proportion of reads that match the phiX genome was estimated

# Proportion of reads matching the phiX genome
reads <- as.character(bam[[1]]$seq)
phi_reads <- isPhiX(reads)
(prop_phi <- round(mean(phi_reads), 4) *100)
## [1] 3.85

# Proportion of unmapped reads matching the phiX genome
unmaped_flags <- bamFlagAsBitMatrix(unique(bam[[1]]$flag))
unmaped_flags <- as.data.frame(unmaped_flags)$isUnmappedQuery
unmaped_flags <- which(as.logical(unmaped_flags))
unmaped_flags <- unique(bam[[1]]$flag)[unmaped_flags]

unmaped_reads <- as.character(bam[[1]]$seq[bam[[1]]$flag %in% unmaped_flags])
phi_unmaped <- isPhiX(unmaped_reads)
(prop_phi_unmaped <- round(mean(phi_unmaped), 4) *100)
## [1] 45.6

In agreement with the idea that unmapped reads may be associated with the phiX DNA spike-in, the proportion of reads estimated to match this genome is 3.85%, corresponding to a total of 45.6% of the unmapped reads.

  1. What is the coverage of each amplicons? Could you find any explanations or clues why the coverage varies among amplicons, especially for those with big differences?

Answer: The coverage of sequencing varies for each amplicon. When normalized to the amplicon size

  • Amplicon 1 shows 1 129 reads per base pair
  • Amplicon 2 shows 42 reads per base pair
  • Amplicon 3 shows 500 reads per base pair
  • Amplicon 4 shows 667 reads per base pair.

Common reasons for variability in coverage include sequence structural properties (e.g. repeats, GC content) and PCR bias. No evidence of major intrinsic differences between sequences was found but there could be differences in PCR amplification efficiency during the target enrichment step, which might have been exponentially amplified. However, it could also be the case that a portion of amplicon 2 is deleted in the genome in study, thus explaining such a dramatic decrease in coverage.

Confirmation: Using the previous chromosome ranges obtained from the BAM file, the overall coverage across chromosome 7 were calculated. The regions with no mapped reads were removed to facilitate the analysis of the resulting plot.

# Chr7 read coverage
cov <- coverage(bam_chr7)[[1]]
# Plot excluding regions of 0 coverage for simplification
plot(cov[cov !=0], type ="l", ylab = "Coverage")

# Check if the peak match expected
position <- 0
regions <- runLength(cov >10000)

for (idx in seq(1, length(regions)-1,2)){
  amplicon <- amplicon_ranges[
    ifelse(idx ==1 , 2, 
           ifelse(idx == 3 , 2, 
                  ifelse(idx== 5, 4, 3)))
    ]
  cat("Amplicon expected range: ", start(amplicon), "-", end(amplicon), "\n")
  position <- position + regions[idx]
  cat("Amplicon starting position: ", position, "\n")
  position <- position + regions[idx+1]
  cat("Amplicon ending position: ", position, "\n\n")
}

  amp_ranges <- bam_chr7[queryHits(overlaps)[subjectHits(overlaps) == amplicon]]
  amp_coverage <- length(amp_ranges) / width(amplicon_ranges)[amplicon]
  cat("Number of reads per size of ", amplicon, ":", amp_coverage , "\n")
  
}

The four amplicon regions show the highest coverage for chromosome 7. Amplicon 1 (second peak) shows the highest coverage, followed by amplicon 4 and 3 (third and fourth peak respectively). Amplicon 2 (first peak), shows a very reduced coverage when compared to the remaining amplicons. Differences in coverage generally result from intrinsic sequence properties or PCR bias. In order to understand why amplicon 2 shows such a reduced coverage the GC ratio of each amplicon was analysed, as this could influence the read coverage.

The reverse pair 2 appears to have a very high CG content (73%) which may reduce its amplification efficiency. Additionally, reverse primers 3 and 4 have a melting temperatures (Tm) below 60C, when all the remaining primers have a Tm around 70C. These differences could result in lower efficiency during the PCR enrichment step. However, this can only be confirmed by estimating PCR efficiencies experimentally. Finally, because amplicon 2 coverage is so reduced, it could also be the case that it corresponds to a real result and amplicon 2 could be deleted from the genome being studied.

  1. What variants/mutations can you identify from this data? How can you evaluate which variants is more real than others?

Answer: Variants/mutations were identified across the genome with 38% of all variants being called on chromosome 7. The only variant identified predicted to be non-synonymous was the amplicon 1 15 bp deletion, which is expected to result in the loss of glu-leu-arg-glu-ala at the protein level of the EGFR transcripts containing the corresponding exon. 4 of the 15 bases associated with the identified deletion were matched to the dbSNP reference database and variants in these positions are likely pathogenic.

Besides testing functional effects and reference databases, to evaluate which variants are more likely to be real, one could additionally compare various calling methodologies (e.g. Freebayes, GATK), as each method is known to show bias to identify particular types of variants (e.g. SNPs, indels).

Confirmation: Many variant calling softwares are available, but samtools pileup was for simplicity and easy R integration. Variants were called if they had a minimum base and mapping quality of 20 and a minimum depth of 500, including deletions and insertions.

variants <- pileup("sequenceFile/aln_sorted.bam", 
  index = "sequenceFile/aln.bam.bai",
  pileupParam=PileupParam(
    max_depth=50000,
    min_base_quality=20, 
    min_mapq=20, 
    min_nucleotide_depth=500, 
    include_deletions=TRUE, 
    include_insertions=TRUE,
    distinguish_strands=FALSE))

Amplicon 2 shows the most variants identified, which could be associated with the low coverage previously noticed, even though no deletions were found for this region. Since the amplicons of interest map to EGFR exons, it is important to understand if these variants can have functional effects at the protein level.

Most of the called variants (97%) are expected to be synonymous mutations and thus have no effect on the protein function. However, 75 transcripts show potential ‘not translated’ phenotype. These 75 transcripts are the result of 15 deleted bases found on amplicon 1. Looking carefully at these bases, it would appears that the region from 55 242 466 to 55 242 480 corresponds to an unique deletion of GAATTAAGAGAAGCA on amplicon 1, leading to the loss of glu-leu-arg-glu-ala at the protein level.

Comparison of the identified variants with curated databases such as dbSNP provides additional confidence to the results, as variants known to occur in the population are more likely to be true positives.
